O:8:"stdClass":22:{s:2:"id";s:3:"494";s:8:"category";s:3:"136";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"name";s:12:"Scenario 6.2";s:12:"questiontext";s:1575:"<h5><span style="border: 0px none; font-stretch: inherit; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline;"><span style="border-image-source: initial; border-image-slice: initial; border-image-width: initial; border-image-outset: initial; border-image-repeat: initial; font-stretch: inherit;">Scenario 2: Keeping records<img src="@@PLUGINFILE@@/Clive.jpg" alt="man looking down at desk" width="105" height="93" style="float:right; margin: 0 0 0 .5em;" class="img-responsive"></span></span></h5><p></p><p>Peter works for Parks and Wildlife as a conservation employee. Peter is well-respected by his colleagues and managers and is regularly called on to perform higher duties when his supervisor is on leave. However, a shadow is cast over Peter's career when he is accused of misconduct.&nbsp;</p><p>Peter's manager, Clive, is outraged that Peter is being accused of misconduct as he has witnessed Peter's outstanding work over the years and is sure he has done nothing wrong.&nbsp;</p><p>As part of the investigation Clive is approached for records relating to the misconduct allegation, but he cannot find the files he needs. He also has no formal record of Peter's work performance over the years as he has never engaged Peter in the Performance Development Plan (PDP) process.&nbsp;<br></p><p style="text-align: right;"><span style="border: 0px none; font-stretch: inherit; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline;"><span style="font-size: 10.5px; line-height: 0px;">Image courtesy of imagerymajestic / FreeDigitalPhotos.net</span></span></p><p></p><p></p>";s:18:"questiontextformat";s:1:"1";s:15:"generalfeedback";s:0:"";s:21:"generalfeedbackformat";s:1:"1";s:11:"defaultmark";d:0;s:7:"penalty";d:0;s:5:"qtype";s:11:"description";s:6:"length";s:1:"0";s:5:"stamp";s:47:"learning-uat.dpaw.wa.gov.au+150511093901+nfzzuo";s:7:"version";s:47: